1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:01,740
Python is a language,

2

00:00:01,740  -->  00:00:06,620
so we need to think about the words and the phrases that make up Python's vocabulary.

3

00:00:06,620  -->  00:00:09,260
These are known as Python's Lexis.

4

00:00:09,260  -->  00:00:11,820
Think of it as a dictionary that tells you what types

5

00:00:11,820  -->  00:00:14,940
of tokens or words Python will understand.

6

00:00:14,940  -->  00:00:18,320
Python has about 30 keyword identifiers,

7

00:00:18,320  -->  00:00:19,850
such as and,

8

00:00:19,850  -->  00:00:21,425
is, for,

9

00:00:21,425  -->  00:00:24,100
while, del, class,

10

00:00:24,100  -->  00:00:28,205
continue, finally, accept, and many more.

11

00:00:28,205  -->  00:00:31,700
Don't worry about memorizing all of these right now. There's a lot.

12

00:00:31,700  -->  00:00:36,840
We'll get more familiar with these through an iterative approach across this course.

13

00:00:36,840  -->  00:00:41,040
So these will become second nature to you the more that you're reintroduced to them.

14

00:00:41,040  -->  00:00:43,360
Just know that there are specific keywords that tell

15

00:00:43,360  -->  00:00:47,420
Python how to do very specific commands and actions.

16

00:00:47,420  -->  00:00:49,840
Also a fun fact about Python is that

17

00:00:49,840  -->  00:00:52,740
the print statement was considered a keyword in Python 2,

18

00:00:52,740  -->  00:00:55,095
but then it became a function in Python 3.

19

00:00:55,095  -->  00:00:57,360
This shows how languages evolve,

20

00:00:57,360  -->  00:01:00,480
just like any language, and Python is no exception.

21

00:01:00,480  -->  00:01:03,460
Usually, when you learn a programming language for the first time,

22

00:01:03,460  -->  00:01:06,080
you'll write hello world as a fun introduction.

23

00:01:06,080  -->  00:01:09,300
So we're going to do that in a demo momentarily.
